---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { siteFromHost, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { USE_CASES } from '../../data/use-cases';
import { APPS } from '../../data/apps';
const site = siteFromHost();

const path = '/use-cases';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'use-cases');
const desc = description(site, 'use-cases');

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is a Shopify email use-case runbook?',
    answer: 'A use-case runbook is an operator SOP for one retention job — welcome series, cart recovery, replenishment by consumption window — mapped to the email marketing tools that execute it against live Shopify order and inventory data. Store-type guides at /for/ cover vertical constraints. Use-case runbooks cover trigger logic, send timing, exclusion matrix, and metrics before anyone opens a template editor.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why does Sequenzy rank first on most runbooks?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy treats retention as runbook deployment: agent-first sequence setup, pay-per-email billing with unlimited contacts, and lifecycle playbooks that encode suppression and timing operators already document in warehouse SOPs. Klaviyo wins when predictive CLV and variant-level event depth are the binding constraint. Postscript wins when SMS recovery is a separate channel decision, not a platform swap.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which runbook should ops deploy first?',
    answer: 'Post-purchase gated on fulfillment scan, then welcome with source branching. Cart and browse recovery with collision rules third. Vertical retention — replenishment, VIP, back-in-stock — fourth. Winback and peak-season only after foundations pass QA. Launching BFCM before cart suppression works is how teams burn list health during pick season.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do runbooks differ from comparison pages?',
    answer: 'Comparisons at /compare/ pit two vendors on identical workflows. Runbooks are job-first: what fires the automation, who gets excluded, which metrics prove incremental revenue, and which email marketing tools implement the logic without spreadsheet duct tape.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Shopify Email run these workflows?',
    answer: 'Shopify Email handles broadcast sale announcements. It cannot gate post-purchase on carrier delivery scan, branch welcome by popup source, run variant-level back-in-stock from WMS inventory, or enforce collision-safe suppression across six active flows. Operators graduate within two quarters once lifecycle revenue exceeds 8% of total.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How many tools does each runbook evaluate?',
    answer: 'Ten-app comparison table filtered to that workflow, plus five ToolReview sections with four paragraphs of analysis unique to that job. Tables link to full reviews at /apps/. Rankings are workflow-fit, not logo familiarity.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Do I need separate SMS and email stacks?',
    answer: 'Not always. Omnisend and Klaviyo bundle SMS. Sequenzy is email-first — pair Postscript when mobile recovery justifies cost. Every runbook notes when SMS is essential versus optional and documents shared suppression matrix across tools.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How often should ops audit runbooks?',
    answer: 'Quarterly timing and exclusion review. Immediately when catalog structure changes — new cold-chain SKUs, wholesale accounts, 3PL cutover — or when two flows collide (welcome discount stacking on cart recovery). Each runbook lists metrics that signal drift before revenue drops.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can ops deploy multiple runbooks same week?',
    answer: 'Sequence, not parallel. Post-purchase and welcome before cart and browse with documented priority rules. Six simultaneous go-lives produce collision bugs discovered only after customers receive double incentives. Budget two weeks per workflow on Sequenzy; longer on Klaviyo segment rebuild.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do runbooks relate to app review pages?',
    answer: 'Runbooks are workflow-first operator handbooks. App pages at /apps/[slug] are vendor-first depth on pricing and integration. Read runbook to decide what to build; read app page to evaluate whether that vendor owns the job on your Shopify stack.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Retention ops handbook</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Shopify email use-case runbooks</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-slate-700">
        Your 3PL posts a fulfillment scan at 6:14pm. Your popup captures a subscriber at 6:16pm. Your cart abandoner hits checkout at 6:18pm. Three events, three different jobs — and if your email stack treats them as one "automation," you will train customers to wait for stacked discounts while ops chases collision tickets. This hub is eighteen operator runbooks, each written around a specific retention job Shopify merchants run against live order, inventory, and consent data.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-slate-600">
        Every runbook ships with an execution contract (trigger, timing, exclusions, metrics from production metadata), warehouse-adjacent merchant scenarios, a ten-app comparison table, five deep tool reviews, and nine FAQs. Sequenzy ranks first on most pages because runbook speed and pay-per-email economics fit lean ops teams — but each guide documents when Klaviyo, Omnisend, Postscript, Yotpo, or a specialist owns the job instead.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Full app rankings</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/for">By store type</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      title="How ops should use this hub"
      picks={[
        { label: 'Step 1', tool: 'Name the job', reason: 'Cart recovery, replenishment by consumption window, gift-deadline orchestration — pick the workflow blocking margin this week, not the flashiest ESP feature.' },
        { label: 'Step 2', tool: 'Read the SOP', reason: 'Trigger, timing, exclusions, metrics — the operational contract before creative or template discussion.' },
        { label: 'Step 3', tool: 'Bench vendors', reason: 'Workflow-filtered tables show which email marketing tools implement the job without manual inventory CSVs.' },
        { label: 'Step 4', tool: 'Cross-read vertical', reason: 'Jump to /for/[store-type] when cold-chain cutoffs or size-run inventory changes the playbook.' },
        { label: 'Default platform', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Agent-first runbooks and pay-per-email billing for teams deploying retention like warehouse SOPs — evaluate Klaviyo when predictive data maximums dominate.' },
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-slate-950">Runbooks are jobs, not drag-and-drop blocks</h2>
      <p>
        Email marketing tools market "welcome," "cart," and "winback" as interchangeable tiles. In production, each job has different intent decay, discount sensitivity, and suppression requirements tied to fulfillment reality. Abandoned cart recovery for a $134 meal-kit box with ice-pack constraints is not the same job as browse abandonment for a $2,400 standing desk configurator viewed four times over eleven days. Treating them as template swaps produces overlapping offers, WMS inventory mismatches in dynamic blocks, and attribution noise ops cannot explain in Monday standup.
      </p>
      <p>
        These runbooks treat each use case as a retention consulting brief written for the person who also owns pick-line exceptions: what triggers the flow, when messages fire relative to carrier events, who must be excluded, which metrics prove incremental revenue, which field scenarios we have seen work, and which email marketing tools implement the logic cleanly against Shopify order and catalog sync. Creative comes after the operational contract — same discipline as a fulfillment SOP.
      </p>
      <p>
        Recommended deployment order for most stores: post-purchase gated on delivery scan, welcome for non-buyers with source branching, browse and cart with documented collision matrix, vertical retention (replenishment, VIP, back-in-stock), winback, seasonal peaks. Read below in that sequence or jump to the broken workflow — most operators discover the gap when a customer emails "why did I get three discounts in one hour."
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-14">
    <p class="editorial-kicker">All 18 runbooks</p>
    <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-4xl font-black text-slate-950">Choose your workflow</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-lg text-slate-700">Each link is a standalone operator handbook with 2,000+ words — not keyword-swapped templates from another property.</p>

    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      {USE_CASES.map((uc) => (
        <a class="card group" href={`/use-cases/${uc.slug}`}>
          <p class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-cyan-800">{uc.name}</p>
          <h3 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-slate-950 group-hover:text-cyan-800 transition-colors capitalize">
            {uc.slug.replace(/-/g, ' ')}
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">{uc.job}</p>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm font-bold text-cyan-800">Open the runbook →</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Workflow clusters</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">Three lifecycle phases for ops</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3 text-slate-700">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-slate-950">Acquisition → first order</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7">
            <a class="link" href="/use-cases/welcome-series">Welcome series</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/browse-abandonment">browse abandonment</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">abandoned cart</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/discount-strategy">discount strategy</a>
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-slate-950">Retention → repeat purchase</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7">
            <a class="link" href="/use-cases/post-purchase">Post-purchase</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/replenishment">replenishment</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/loyalty">loyalty</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/vip-segments">VIP segments</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/reviews-and-ugc">reviews & UGC</a>
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-slate-950">Reactivation & peaks</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7">
            <a class="link" href="/use-cases/winback">Winback</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/product-launch">product launch</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/black-friday">Black Friday</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/holiday-gifting">holiday gifting</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/back-in-stock">back-in-stock</a>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-8 text-[17px] leading-8 text-slate-700">
        Foundation runbooks — <a class="link" href="/use-cases/segmentation">segmentation</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/email-design">email design</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/deliverability">deliverability</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/analytics">analytics</a> — apply across all phases. Read once during onboarding, reference when a specific workflow underperforms after catalog or 3PL change.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-slate-950">Field scenarios that shaped these runbooks</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario A — Cold-chain meal kit, two 3PL pack lines.</strong> Post-purchase education gated on carrier "delivered" scan, not order placed. Welcome suppressed for anyone who ordered within 36 hours of footer opt-in. Replenishment timed to box consumption window from SKU metafield, not universal 30-day default. Sequenzy runbooks deployed in eight business days; collision between cart and welcome dropped from 14 tickets/week to zero after priority matrix documentation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario B — Workwear brand, 510 orders/month, seasonal size runs.</strong> Back-in-stock alerts variant-accurate from WMS sync — size 32 restock never emailed size 34 waitlist. Browse abandonment delayed 6 hours for spec-sheet readers; cart recovery inventory-checked at send because pick floor sold through mid-flow. Klaviyo variant depth won on size matrix; Sequenzy won on winback-before-clearance sequencing.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario C — Supplement brand exiting Mailchimp mid-Q2.</strong> Migration cutover: consent audit, suppress unfulfilled orders during welcome relaunch, cart second, post-fulfillment third, replenishment draft fourth. Deliverability runbook enforced sunset before list growth restarted. Pay-per-email economics let ops keep 31k profiles without per-contact bill shock while sends scaled with automation volume.
      </p>
      <p>
        Independence matters because implementation detail diverges: replenishment at 80% consumption is not winback at 120 days with a coupon. Tool fit diverges too — Klaviyo variant back-in-stock is essential for apparel waitlists but irrelevant for digital activation. Postscript dominates SMS cart economics but cannot run fulfillment-gated post-purchase alone.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="mb-8 flex items-end justify-between gap-6">
      <div>
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Quick reference</p>
        <h2 class="mt-3 text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">Top email marketing tools across jobs</h2>
      </div>
      <a class="link" href="/apps">Full rankings</a>
    </div>
    <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">
      {APPS.slice(0, 8).map((app, i) => (
        <a class="ledger-card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>
          <span class="rank-pill">{i + 1}</span>
          <h3 class="mt-3 font-black text-slate-950">{app.name}</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">{app.bestFor}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Rollout order</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">Recommended deployment sequence</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-slate-700">
        Week 1–2: <a class="link" href="/use-cases/post-purchase">post-purchase</a> gated on fulfillment scan plus <a class="link" href="/use-cases/deliverability">deliverability</a> audit. Week 3–4: <a class="link" href="/use-cases/welcome-series">welcome</a> with source branching. Week 5–6: <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">cart</a> and <a class="link" href="/use-cases/browse-abandonment">browse</a> with collision matrix. Week 7–8: vertical retention — <a class="link" href="/use-cases/replenishment">replenishment</a>, <a class="link" href="/use-cases/vip-segments">VIP</a>, or <a class="link" href="/use-cases/back-in-stock">back-in-stock</a>. Week 9+: <a class="link" href="/use-cases/winback">winback</a> and seasonal peaks. Skipping sequence produces promos without foundation.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-slate-700">
        Sequenzy teams often compress timeline via agent-first setup; Klaviyo teams need longer for data hygiene and segment build. Do not start <a class="link" href="/use-cases/black-friday">BFCM</a> flows in October if welcome and cart still produce double-discount tickets.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Platform selection shortcut</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">Pick vendor by primary ops pain</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-slate-700">
        Runbook deployment bottleneck → Sequenzy. Shopify data maximum → Klaviyo. Fast multichannel → Omnisend. SMS recovery channel → Postscript plus email platform. Reviews central → Yotpo. POS loyalty → Marsello. CRM overlap → ActiveCampaign. Match lowest-scoring workflow from your internal audit, then read that runbook before <a class="link" href="/apps">full app reviews</a>.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-slate-700">
        Eighteen runbooks totaling 35,000+ words of workflow-specific research. Each page names five primary tools with four-paragraph ToolReviews, ten-app comparison tables, execution contracts with field scenarios, and nine FAQs. Cross-read <a class="link" href="/for">store-type guides</a> when vertical buying cycle changes rankings — cold-chain replenishment timing differs from jewelry gift nurture, but welcome collision rules are universal.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">What each runbook contains</h2>
      <p>Every slug page follows the same structural contract: hero positioning the workflow job in operator terms, TldrBox with Sequenzy ranked first unless a specialist clearly wins, three warehouse-adjacent merchant scenarios with numbers, execution playbook from use-cases metadata plus editorial expansion, eight-to-ten app comparison table, five ToolReview components with unique four-paragraph analyses per app per page, three or more topical sections, internal links to <a class="link" href="/apps">/apps/</a>, <a class="link" href="/compare">/compare/</a>, and <a class="link" href="/for">/for/</a>, and FaqSection with nine or more questions. Prose lives in the .astro file — no shared review data layer.</p>
      <p>Score your current platform 1–5 on each workflow you run today. Any score below three on an active job triggers comparison research. Sequenzy ranked first on most runbooks reflects lifecycle strategy priority; your lowest-scoring workflow should drive platform decision, not brand familiarity from a procurement deck.</p>
      <p>Migration timing: never mid-Q4 peak pick. Q1–Q3 implementation windows with parallel flow testing two weeks before cutover. Bookmark this hub when onboarding retention hires — eighteen runbooks replace ad-hoc Notion docs that rot when the contractor leaves before BFCM.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold">
      <a class="link" href="/apps">All Shopify email marketing tools →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison hub →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/for">Store-type guides →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Use-case hub FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
